stantiated directly, but only the `ChangeLogProperty` constructor requires reflection. The `ReflectionSerializer` accesses nested helper fields and methods without needing public constructors. \\\\n\\\\nHmm, making these nested helpers package-private might reduce accessibility, but I worry about the `ObjectUtil` calling public methods if the nested class isn’t public. This could cause issues unless `setAccessible` is used, which `ObjectUtil` doesn’t do. So, it looks like the `Escaped` helper class needs to be public for its setters to work.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering access modifiers in serialization**\\\\n\\\\nI’m thinking about the `ParentSerializable`, which doesn’t have setters, and how the `ReflectionSerializer` accesses fields. Can I keep fields package-private since they’re directly instantiated by the test? There's the active class calling `getSerializableFields`, and the `ReflectionSerializer` can set accessible fields on package-private classes without issues.\\\\n\\\\nHowever, I wonder if it's safer to have them public. It seems that native configurations with `$` are unavoidable for nested public classes. I might need to use the `access-filter` with exact class patterns like \\\\\\\"java.util.Date\\\\\\\" to potentially match inner classes as well.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_Hi5RJzcMiv0cemP6TbEkLZON|fc_0257d767d56de5ab0169f6348835d0819c8ea45b402cdbd838\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"git status --short\"}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 1537, \"output\": 1030, \"cacheRead\": 52736, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 55303, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1777742967402, \"responseId\": \"resp_0257d767d56de5ab0169f63477f9e0819cb6de07a9840a8f2e\"}, \"toolResults\": [{\"role\": \"toolResult\", 